AGI - "We ask Russia to stop these measures and reverse what we have mentioned right now and to seek acceptable solutions with European companies targeted by the Russian regime." The EU spokesman for Foreign Policy, Peter Stano, said this, answering a question on the case &nbsp;Ariston&nbsp; in the daily briefing with the press. "I can only repeat that this demonstrates and confirms that Russia is an unpredictable actor, both on the international and political scene, even in the economic field, and has created an entrepreneurial climate that is arbitrary and hostile to foreign investors," he explained.
&nbsp;
"And I think this is a very strong message for all those who are considering continuing business in Russia or even doing business in Russia, going anyway to Russia, what kind of environment can expect in Russia. And of course, the European Union and its Member States, of course in contact with the companies concerned, are examining the whole situation and seeing what next steps should be taken," said Stano, who recalled the "waves of sanctions" already adopted against Moscow.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"These measures by Russian authorities and the Russian regime against legitimate economic activities are yet another proof of Russia's contempt for international law. And it is also a huge signal for anyone, for economic operators, for anyone active in the economic field, what kind of credibility Russia has when it comes to economic environment," Stano.&nbsp insisted.

