&nbsp;AGI - Student protests pro-Gaza in American colleges > entered in the second week, just as in many universities approaches the ceremony of deliveries of graduate degrees. There are hundreds of protesters arrested so far in all the United States. The slogan became a symbol of the protest is "divest", which would be the opposite of investing but has a different shade to "disinvest": students ask university leaders to cut economic relations with Israel, either by selling quotas in Israeli companies or by getting out of agreements with companies doing business with Israel.
&nbsp;
Columbia University, for example, one of the most prestigious American universities, has more than 13 billion dollars invested in companies, such as Microsoft and Airbnb, > doing business with Israel. Other schools, such as Cornell and Yale, have asked the leaders to put an end to investment in arms-producing companies. No universities, so far, have accepted the demands>.&nbsp;Alla Columbia, New York, the most delicate situation is recorded, after the ultimatum given by the school board to the protesters to leave the campus. The school summit announced the start of suspensions from the university to those who did not leave the area. The ultimatum has expired for three hours and students have announced that they will continue the occupation. "We will not be intimidated - the protesters have said - by these attempts to suffocate the student protest."
&nbsp;
At the University of Texas, in Austin, riot agents arrested six people, but they would not result in students but outsiders who used the campus to carry out protests. The police said they kidnapped baseball bats. In Virginia Tech the police stopped ninety people, of which 54 students. Numerous arrests also at the University of Georgia, in Athens, where tents were set up on campus. The University of Pennsylvania has placed around the school area a series of signs with the notice to "do not exceed" private property. The leaders of Brown University, in the state of Rhode Island, offered protesters the opportunity to discuss in May the possible resignation of economic relations with Israel provided that the campus is "freed peacefully in the coming days and no other demonstrations of unauthorised protest are put into effect."
